defaultMobile Games - 
defaultPEGI for APPS
default and IARC
defaultThe rise
default of smartphones and tablets as gaming platforms has been a vital part of the evolution of the games industry in recent years. 
defaultPEGI for APPS, a rating procedure specifically designed for small software applications, including
default but not limited to games, was launched in 2012 to address this important market shift. It is designed to cater specifically to the needs of app developers and digital platform operators. It is not a new rating system, it is a more flexible and tailor-made
default procedure that allows mobile or digital platforms to use the classic PEGI rating system as it is known from boxed products and online titles. On top of that, it adds new feature descriptors that inform a consumer about certain types of functionality in an
default app. Currently, PEGI for Apps is used by Microsoft on Windows 8 and Windows Mobile platforms.
defaultAlthough app platforms still have local storefronts for customers it 
defaulthas become clear that 
defaultpublishers are in need of a one-stop-shop to get all age classificatio
defaultns for their products in one streamlined process. Therefore, an international working group, including rating boards from Europe, US, Australia, Brazil and others, is working on a global solution under the name of IARC (International Alliance for Rating Co
defaultntent): a list of questions that combines all the criteria of the different rating boards across th
defaulte globe into one big flowchart.
defaultPEGI for Apps has been part of this project from the start. The IARC program will provide for a streamlined submission proces
defaults in order to produce classifications for all participating regions at the same time. Although depending on cultural differences, these ratings may vary the system provides a publisher with a single, robust solution and takes away a lot of hassle. IARC is 
defaultexpected to be launched at the end of 2013.
default&#xa0;
defaultInternet Filters – Significant Risk defaultof defaultOver-BlockingdefaultWe have particular concerns about the 
defaultpotential for unintended consequences from the universal internet filtering that was announced by the Prime Minister in 
defaultJuly.
defaultUkie have always supported an ‘active choice’ approach to parental internet controls, as emphasised in our response to the DCMS consultation on the issue last year. The approach being 
defaultproposed
default, where controls will be 
defaultswitched
default on by default
default,
default goes a st
defaultep beyond this.
defaultWhilst the protection of children is of course paramount, 
defaulthaving controls in place by default  
defaultgreatly increases the importance of ensuring that they are 
defaultwell targeted
default and do not 
defaultinadvertently 
defaultblock 
defaultor restrict access to content that is not
default in fact inappropriate for children
default.
defaultWe understand that discussions are still taking place with ISPs, and that the final design of the filters is not in place. However, the only example already in place is the filtering that Talk Talk offer to all customer
defaults under the HomeSafe brand, and we have specific concerns about this system. 
defaultAccording to the Talk Talk website promoting their HomeSafe technology, parents are given a list of categories of ‘inappropriate websites’ from which they can select which to blo
defaultck. These different categories are:
defaultThe inclusion of ‘Games’ in such a list is deeply troubling to our industry. 
defaultW
defaulte recognise the value to parents of controls enabling them to restrict access to 
defaultgames that contain 
defaultmature
default 
defaultcontent (
defaultfor example
default when they are 
defaultPEGI 
defaultage rated 18)
default if they choose to do so
default, as 
defaultunder
default existing parental controls systems, but 
defaultsimply
default filtering out all games 
defaultis
default a
defaultn extremely
default blunt approach that 
defaultwe believe is unnecessary
default and
default disproportionate
default,
default 
defaultand 
defaultcould potentially have 
defaultvery 
defaultadverse effects on the UK games industry
default.
default It should be noted that only a small proportion of games are age-rated 18
default. In 2012, for example, just 9.4% of PEGI-rated games received an 18 rating.
default Indeed, in the last ten years just 5.7% of games rated were PEGI 18.
defaultThis
default proposal
default seems to ignore the difference between the content and the medium. It would be absurd to have 
defaultan option for websites about ‘books’ or ‘films’ to be classed as inappropriate by their nature, without regard to the content, nature or rating of the individual products. It is equally wrong for the same to be applied to games. 
defaultWe strongly disagree with 
defaultthis approach, and are discussing it actively
default with Talk Talk to learn how it 
defaultis applied and what impact it is having.
defaultWe are very 
defaultconcern
defaulted
default that 
defaultfiltering “games” as a category of inappropriate websites 
defaultcould be
default held up as an example of best practice: it m
defaultust not become government policy that this should be adopted by all ISPs. 
defaultWhile the industry agrees that
default the protection of children is 
defaulttantamount, 
defaultthe solution should be tailored appropriately to address the specific concern and not be so overly broad that
default it will have extreme and inappropriate consequences.
defaultThe potential commercial risk is clear:  if a large portion of the UK population had all websites related to games blocked from their internet connection automatically, the impact on the games industry 
defaultcould be significant.  More importantly, this filtering would block content that is well outside the scope of 
defaultthe adult material that this program seeks to address.
defaultFor example, application of a broad filter for all “games” will create a 
defaultsignificant risk t
defaulthat 
defaultgames specifically intended for young people, including 
defaulteducational games
default,
default will be 
defaultautomatically 
defaultblocked by filters targeting those issues.
default 
defaultThe game industry does not believe this is in the best interest of UK children or 
defaultsomething
default that parents want or need.  This is evidenced in the statistic used earlier in the document that 40% of parents are aware of the parental controls that exist on their games consoles and choose not to use them, as they are already confident that they have 
defaultsufficient control over their children’s habits. There are a large number of well-informed, technologically savvy parents in the UK, and blocking access to games websites without their consent would do great damage to the system’s credibility. 
defaultWe strongly
default recommend that, as the government works with each ISP on implementation of the new filters, it does not promote the inclusion of ‘games’ as a category of inappropriate websites. 
defaultAdditionally, even filters that more specifically target content about “dati
defaultng,” “drugs” or “alcohol,” may have unintended consequences that are detrimental to children.  For example, a game teaching children about sexual health, drug addiction or other issues is likely to be caught by the filters and so inaccessible to the childr
defaulten it is designed to help. 
defaultMany of these games can be discovered on sites which are not explicitly labelled as “education” or “charity”, in order to be discovered organically by the young people they are targeted towards
default, making it even more difficult for 
defaultfilters to intelligently detect and allow them
default.
defaultMuch greater information is needed on how the filters will work in practice, 
defaultincluding 
defaulthow quickly incorrect blocks on websites can be reported and removed.
